<script type="application/json" data-for="htmlwidget-14dea25257fefb4eb3ba">{"x":{"filter":"none","vertical":false,"data":[["Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of informed consent process and informed consentform (ICF)","Creation of informed consent process and informed consentform (ICF)","Creation of questionnaires and other study tools                   ","Creation of questionnaires and other study tools                   ","Creation of questionnaires and other study tools                   ","Creation of questionnaires and other study tools                   "],["One PPI representative co-creates or reviews          ","A group of PPI representatives co-create or review    ","A group of PPI representatives co-create or review    ","A group of PPI representatives co-create or review    ","PPI representatives provide a formal letter of support","Reviewing by crowdsourcing                            ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   "],["A Protocol Advisor was involved. The Protocol Advisor, living with HIV and part of the military HIV programme, made suggestions and recommendations based on personal experiences and knowledge. He provided important feedback from the perspective of the patient with issues specific and not-so-specific to the military, issues regarding confidentiality, sexuality, drug and alcohol use, and the difference between military duties and responsibilities throughout the protocol stages.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               ","On average, each siteâ€™s Community Advisory Board consisted of 13â€“19 stakeholders, including leaders of HIV/AIDS-related Community-based Organisations, hospital-based HIV/AIDS service providers, and HIV/AIDS network leaders in minority communities. CABs meet once a month at the research site or in the agencies or community organizations represented by the CAB members. The meetings are conducted by the project director and research staff. The CAB reviewed the study protocol and made suggestions regarding the language used in the protocols to avoid stigmatizing the community. For example, the CAB recommended that the study protocol should specify that the study is not only about reducing HIV risks but also about improving healthy relationships among black couples and about learning strategies for a healthy lifestyle.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      ","Working group members facilitated workshops with youth to train them in research methods and collaboratively designed the protocol. In all, 27 youth participated in an iterative protocol planning process.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   ","Consultation in the format of focus group discussions to inform the design of a clinical trial to reduce postnatal transmission of HIV. Participants: HIV-positive mothers. Mothers consulted raised concerns about the amount of blood that was planned to be taken from mothers and their babies as detailed in the draft protocol. The mothers were asked to consider what would be an acceptable amount of blood to be taken for the purpose of the research. After the consultation, the protocol was amended to reduce the quantity of blood to be taken to a level that was acceptable to mothers but still adequate for laboratory analyses. Before data collection, the interviewers participated in a 2-week training course. Question guides were translated into the local language, Chichewa, and back-translated into English. All interviews and focus group discussions were audio-taped, simultaneously transcribed and translated verbatim into English by the interviewer directly after the interviews and focus group discussions were conducted, and then subsequently reviewed by investigators.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        ","PPI representatives wrote a letter of support for a project funding proposal                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   ","Community feedback on the informed consent process was collected by transforming the 20-page informed consent form into a series of interactive, plain-language, animated video modules, which were screened at an open public discussion. The modules were created by a local community-based organization that specializes in translating clinical science to lay audiences through creative products. The event was advertised via Facebook (295 followers) and Twitter (329 followers) accounts of our research group. We also distributed physical copies of the event flyers at both a local infectious disease clinic and a clinical research center. We additionally sent the event information to local HIV community engagement advocates. Importantly, we solicited the assistance of a community member known to our research group as a highly engaged local HIV advocate who had previously participated in crowdsourcing research conducted by our group.\nAfter screening, the participants discussed which parts of the informed consent modules were easiest and most difficult to understand, what additional information they thought a trial participant should know (i.e. what was missing from the modules), and what additional formats would be useful for conveying informed consent information to potential trial participants. This discussion was guided by a facilitator. To obtain a sufficient participation to benefit from multiple perspectives, we offered attendance incentives of a $15 gift card per attendee and also provided lunch. Ultimately a total of 20 people participated in-person at the event. We collected 1h of audio-recorded feedback.","The four PPI workshops, lasting approximately 90 minutes each, were conducted in May and June 2022: two for young people and one each for GBMSM and people from black communities. Recruitment of workshop participants used social media targeted at local community groups and the National Institute for Health and Care Research Applied Research Collaboration-West Young Personâ€™s Advisory Group. The workshops included 9 young people (6 female), 4 GBMSM and 6 from black communities (all female). Contributors were paid for their time. All feedback (both positive and negative comments) about the elements and features of the vending machine interface, the promotional material and the participant information forms was collated and tab lated into a PBA â€˜table of changesâ€™. The â€˜table of changesâ€™ enabled systematic collation of feedback and prioritisation of potential changes. A six-point coding framework was used to decide the importance of each proposed change and required consideration of whether the change was important to behaviour change; easy to implement and not controversial; repeatedly stated in the feedback; supported by the experience of either the users, stakeholders or reported in the literature; did not contradict the logic model; or not to be implemented, for example, because it was unfeasible. Changes were then prioritised using the MoSCoW framework (Must do; Should do; Could do; Would like to do) based on their importance to behaviour change and ease of implementation.                                                                                                                                       ","We reviewed a new PROUD study questionnaire by email with 6 community members and 6 participants                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               ","Researchers worked with several young people (mostly from community facilities) to test interviews, improve the design of study materials and develop a video explaining the study to potential participants                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   ","Three PPI members with lived experience of HIV, three people who had attended a dentist in the last twelve months and two people with lived experience of homelessness. Collaboration with wider study stakeholders including public health dentists and health researchers to create study material as well as training modules. Hybrid meetings.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             ","In this project, our research team included several expert patients. The questionnaire used in the study were revised and edited by two long-standing PPI members of the SHCS and three additional members of the CHUV HIV Community Council were consulted to increase diversity of patient input.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            "],["<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Carey1992'>Carey 1992<\/a>    ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/MottCAB2008'>Mott 2008<\/a>   ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Flicker2008'>Flicker 2006<\/a>","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Boote2010'>Boote 2010<\/a>    ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Lessard2019'>Lessard 2019<\/a>","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/DaySuz2020'>Day 2020<\/a>     ","<a href='https://t.ly/qD-qY'>Gobin 2024<\/a>               ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Gafos2020'>Gafos 2020<